    In solving part (a) of the preceding example, the expression we found for <math xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" xmlns:md="http://cnx.rice.edu/mdml" xmlns="http://cnx.rice.edu/cnxml"><semantics><mrow><mrow><mi>y</mi></mrow><mrow/></mrow><annotation encoding="StarMath 5.0"> size 12&#123;y&#125; &#123;&#125;</annotation></semantics></math> is valid for any projectile motion where air resistance is negligible. Call the maximum height <math xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" xmlns:md="http://cnx.rice.edu/mdml" xmlns="http://cnx.rice.edu/cnxml"><semantics><mrow><mrow><mrow><mi>y</mi><mo stretchy="false">=</mo><mi>h</mi></mrow></mrow><mrow/></mrow><annotation encoding="StarMath 5.0"> size 12&#123;y=h&#125; &#123;&#125;</annotation></semantics></math>; then,
    
